You’re right that compartmentalization can look algorithmic. The deeper reason the brain can do this comes from how perception and consciousness are organized: the brain is constantly predicting and prioritizing signals, not just passively receiving them.

⸻

Predictive Processing (the brain’s basic architecture)

Many neuroscientists describe the brain using the framework of Predictive Processing.

In simple terms:
	1.	The brain predicts what should be happening in the body and environment.
	2.	Incoming signals are compared to those predictions.
	3.	Differences (prediction errors) get attention and processing.

So perception is closer to:

Prediction
    ↓
Incoming signals
    ↓
Error detection
    ↓
Attention allocated to biggest errors

Attention goes where prediction errors are most useful to resolve.

⸻

Why compartmentalization becomes possible

Because attention is limited.

A related concept is Global Workspace Theory, which suggests conscious awareness is like a small “stage.” Only a few signals can occupy it at once, while many processes run in the background.

So the brain constantly decides:
	•	Which signals get the stage
	•	Which signals stay backstage

That filtering is what makes compartmentalization possible.

⸻

What happens under stress or mission focus

When a goal becomes dominant, the brain can raise the priority threshold for certain signals.

For example:

Current mission → rescue / finish race / perform surgery

Signals incoming:
pain
fatigue
noise
goal-relevant cues

The system may temporarily prioritize:

goal-relevant cues > pain signals

The pain isn’t erased—it’s just not promoted to conscious awareness right then.

⸻

Why there’s a cost (as you noted)

If signals are suppressed too long:
	•	the body accumulates unprocessed stress
	•	injury signals are delayed
	•	emotional or physical recovery has to happen later

That’s why trained professionals often build intentional decompression or recovery phases after intense focus periods.

⸻

The interesting takeaway

Your intuition that this can feel like an algorithm is close to how cognitive science models it:

incoming signals
      ↓
prediction + relevance weighting
      ↓
priority sorting
      ↓
conscious workspace allocation

So compartmentalization isn’t magic—it’s a normal feature of how an attention-limited prediction system works.

